{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141113154553|633678443","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Bill_Owens_(New_York_politician)","to":"Bill Owens (New York politician)"}],"pages":{"23951220":{"pageid":23951220,"ns":0,"title":"Bill Owens (New York politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-11-19T22:03:48Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{for|other persons named Bill Owens| William Owens (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Congressman\n| name             = Bill Owens\n| image            = Bill Owens official photo.jpg\n| state            = New York\n| district         = [[New York's 21st congressional district|21st]]\n| term_start       = January 3, 2013\n| term_end         = <!--January 3, 2015-->\n| predecessor      = [[Paul Tonko]]\n| successor       = [[Elise Stefanik]] <small>(elect)</small>\n| state2            = New York\n| district2         = [[New York's 23rd congressional district|23rd]]\n| term_start2       = November 3, 2009\n| term_end2       = January 3, 2013\n| predecessor2      = [[John M. McHugh]]\n| successor2      = [[Tom Reed (politician)|Tom Reed]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1949|01|20}}\n| birth_place   = [[Brooklyn]], New York\n| party            = Registered independent (1971\u20132009)<br/>[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (2009\u2013present)\n| residence        = [[Plattsburgh, New York]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Manhattan College]] <small>([[Bachelor of Business Administration|B.B.A.]])</small><br/>[[Fordham University School of Law]] <small>([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])</small>\n| profession       = Lawyer, Businessperson\n| spouse           = Jane Owens\n| children         = Three\n| religion         = Roman Catholic\n| website          = {{URL|http://owens.house.gov|Congressman Bill Owens}}\n| branch           = {{air force|United States}}\n| rank             = [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n}}\n\n'''William Lewis \u201cBill\u201d Owens''' (born January 20, 1949) is the  [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|New York|21}}, a post he has held since 2009. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].  The district, the state's largest and most rural, includes most of the [[North Country, New York|North Country]], as well as the northern suburbs of [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]].\n\nOn January 14, 2014, Owens announced he will not seek reelection in the 2014 elections.<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=Maury|title=Bill Owens will not seek re-election|url=http://poststar.com/news/local/bill-owens-will-not-seek-re-election/article_00241ccc-7d40-11e3-8dd2-0019bb2963f4.html|newspaper=Glens Falls Post-Star|date=January 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and military service==\nBorn in [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]] to Lewis Owens and Alice Stanton Owens,<ref name=\"alice\"/> Owens was raised in [[Mineola, New York]]. After graduating from [[Chaminade High School]], where he was a classmate of television host and conservative political commentator [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]], he enlisted in the [[U.S. Air Force]] and was stationed at [[Plattsburgh Air Force Base]]. He returned to the North Country and has lived there for over 30 years after serving as a [[United States Air Force]] captain.\n\nOwens is a 1971 [[summa cum laude]] graduate of [[Manhattan College]] with a degree in [[business administration]] and a 1974 top-half graduate of [[Fordham University School of Law]].\n\n==Law career==\nBefore coming to Congress, Owens was a managing partner at Stafford, Owens, Piller, Murnane & Trombley, where he specialized in business law, international law, and estate and tax law.<ref name=\"soct law\"/> He is also an adjunct professor in business law at [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh]]. In 2004, he was appointed by Governor [[George Pataki]] to the College Council at that university.<ref name=\"appointed\"/> He served as the host for Business Affairs<ref name=\"progamming\"/><ref name=\"hat into ring\"/> on [[WCFE-TV]], a [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS television station]] in Plattsburgh. According to financial disclosure forms filed when he ran for Congress, Owens made $751,000 in 2008, mostly from his law practice.<ref name=\"Observer10062009\"/>\n\nWhen the Plattsburgh Air Force Base closed in 1995, Owens helped create and worked for the Plattsburgh Airbase Redevelopment Corporation (formerly the Plattsburgh Inter-municipal Development Council), which recruited private companies to reuse the space. The base is now home to companies such as [[Bombardier Inc.]], a passenger railway car maker. Plattsburgh Airbase Redevelopment Corporation attests that more than 2,000 jobs were created at the site since the military left.<ref name=\"points to\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2009\n{{Main|New York's 23rd congressional district special election, 2009}}\nOn August 10, 2009, the Democratic Party of [[New York's 23rd congressional district]] chose Owens to run in [[New York's 23rd congressional district special election, 2009|a special election]] to fill the House seat vacated by the incumbent Republican [[John M. McHugh|John McHugh]], who had resigned to take a post as the [[Secretary of the Army]].<ref name=\"democrats nominate\"/> Because he was a registered independent at the time, Owens had to obtain the signatures of all 11 Democratic county chairs in the district to allow him to run as a Democrat.<ref name=\"Observer\"/>\n\nOriginally, Owens faced Republican [[New York State Assembly|Assemblywoman]] [[Dierdre Scozzafava|Dede Scozzafava]] and [[Doug Hoffman]], an accountant from [[Lake Placid, New York|Lake Placid]] who was running as a third party candidate on the single ballot line of the [[Conservative Party of New York]] after failing to also get the Republican Party nomination. \u201cThe race,\u201d wrote Valerie Bauman of the Associated Press, \u201creceived national attention, with some calling it a referendum on Obama and others saying it could help Republicans focus their message to attract more people to the party.\u201d  Bauman said that \u201cDespite the fervor that surrounded Hoffman in the final week of the campaign, Owens managed to appeal to the voters with his talk of job creation and the need for more federal support for Fort Drum (an army base in the district) and farmers.\u201d<ref name=\"NY 23\">{{cite news|last=Bauman|first=Valerie|title=NY 23 Election Results: Bill Owens Beats Doug Hoffman|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/11/03/bill-owens-leads-doug-hof_n_344776.html|work=Huffington Post|date=November 4, 2009}}</ref> Scozzafava was a social liberal, and high-profile conservatives such as [[Rush Limbaugh]], [[Sarah Palin]], and [[Michelle Malkin]] threw their support behind Hoffman, who enjoyed Tea Party support. Under pressure from conservative elements in her party, who saw \u201cDoug Hoffman as the man who would save them,\u201d according to the ''San Francisco Chronicle'', Scozzafava dropped out of the race on October 31, the weekend before the election.<ref name=\"Election results\">{{cite news|title=Election results|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/abraham/2009/11/03/ny-23-election-results-bill-owens-beats-doug-hoffman-glenn-beck-and-rush- limbaugh/|newspaper=SF gate}}</ref> Hoffman became Owens's sole opponent when Scozzafava dropped out of the race on October 31. The ''Watertown Daily Times'', which had originally endorsed Scozzafava, switched its endorsement to Owens on November 1.<ref name=\"changed race\"/> Later on November 1, Scozzafava endorsed Owens.  In the special election, Owens won 49 percent of the vote to 45 percent for Hoffman and 6 percent for Scozzafava. Owens was sworn in on November 6, 2009.  He became the first Democrat to represent what is now the 23rd since 1873.\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2010#District 23}}\n\nOwens almost immediately announced that he would run for a full term in 2010.  He campaigned largely on \u201ccreating jobs throughout his district, attracting foreign manufacturers, taking care of veterans, and ensuring that Fort Drum (an Army installation located in the district) is preserved.\u201d Owens won his re-election bid with a second consecutive [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]] of 47.5% of the vote against Republican and Independence nominee Matthew A. Doheny and Conservative nominee Doug Hoffman, becoming the first Democrat to win a full term in the North Country district in 138 years.\n\nThe election was one of the ten closest Congressional races that year.<ref name=NCN>{{cite news|title=$200,000 Attacking Owens|url=http://northcountrynow.com/news/gop-congressional-candidate-doheny-says-outside-groups-have-already-spent-200000-attacking-incu|newspaper=North County Now|date=December 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2012#District 21}}\nOwens ran for reelection in [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2012|2012]] in the renumbered 21st District.  He faced a rematch against Doheny and was elected to a second full term, albeit narrowly.<ref>http://pressrepublican.com/0100_news/x1499660430/Owens-wins-despite-losing-eight-of-12-counties</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nDuring his campaign, Owens said he would focus on creating jobs throughout his district, attracting foreign manufacturers, taking care of veterans, and ensuring that [[Fort Drum]] is preserved.<ref name=\"Observer\" /><ref name=\"wptz\"/> He has called for deeper federal budget cuts (including 3% cuts across the board for federal agencies), co-sponsored the Budget Process Improvement Act of 2011, and said that the Bush-era tax cuts need to be allowed to expire for people earning over $500,000. Owens is the second thriftiest member of Congress, with staff expenses of $713,969.<ref name=frugal>{{cite news|title=Frelinghuysen\u2019s staff most frugal|url=http://newjerseyhills.com/bernardsville_news/news/frelinghuysen-s-staff-most-frugal/article_d0c22ea4- b79b-11e0-914b-001cc4c03286.html|newspaper=The Bernardsville News|date=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOwens has consistently voted for legislation to build the controversial [[Keystone Pipeline]] to carry tar sand oil across the United States from Canada for export to foreign nations .<ref>OWENS Press Release January 8, 2012 : 113th Congress HR 3</ref>\n\nAs a congressman, Owens first authored piece of legislation was the ''<ref name=\"open congress\"/> Rural Jobs Tax Credit Act'', a bill that, if passed, would create a 15% tax incentive in 2010 for businesses that hire or expand their payroll in rural areas, and a 10% tax incentive for firms that do the same in 2011.\n\nOn December 14, 2011, Marc Heller reported that Sen. [[Claire McCaskill]] had accused Owens and other members of the House Armed Services Committee \u201cof loading up an annual defense bill with pork-barrel projects despite a congressional ban on home-state 'earmarks.'\u201d Owens's earmarks \u201cincluded construction at Fort Drum and $500,000 intended for the Fort Drum Regional Health Planning Organization.\u201d<ref name=PorkBarrel>{{cite news|title=Senator Accuses Owens Of PorkBarrel Projects|url=http://www.ogd.com/article/20111214/OGD01/312149992/-1/ogd01|newspaper=The Journal|date=December 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Gay Marriage\nIn August 2009, Owens stated that he supported [[civil unions]] and believed marriage should  be legally recognized as one man one woman.  Owens opposes any federal action on marriage, which he called a \"states rights issue\".<ref name=\"Observer\"/> In July 2011, after the New York State legislature passed a bill recognizing same-sex marriage in New York, Owens became a co-sponsor of the [[Respect for Marriage Act]], which would repeal the federal [[Defense of Marriage Act]].<ref name=\"hr 1116\"/>\n\n;Labor\nHe supports the [[Employee Free Choice Act]].<ref name=\"why labor\"/>\n\n;Health Care\nOwens voted for the [[Affordable Health Care for America Act]] on November 7, 2009.<ref name=\"roll call 887\"/> He voted against the [[Stupak Amendment]] which proposed to restrict abortion funding in the federal [[health insurance exchange]]s.<ref name=\"no on Stupak\"/> He voted for the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] on March 21, 2010, and for the [[Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act]] of 2010 to incorporate certain agreed-upon changes with the Senate.<ref name=\"roll 165\"/><ref name=\"roll167\"/>\n\n;Internet policy\nIn 2011, Rep. Owens became a co-sponsor of Bill H.R.3261 otherwise known as the [[Stop Online Piracy Act]].<ref name=\"govtrack\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h112-3261 Bill H.R.3261]; GovTrack.us;</ref>\n\n; GMO crops\nOwens is a member of the House Committee on Agriculture<ref>http://owens.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=333193</ref> and voted for the [[Farmer Assurance Provision]].<ref>http://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/113-2013/h62</ref> Owens says that he is \"still doing the fact-finding\" when it comes to Monsanto and GMO crops. \"I have farmers who are telling me it's a great thing. I have people telling me that it's the worst thing in the world.\"<ref>http://www.northcountrypublicradio.org/news/story/22324/for-north-country-beekeepers-death-and-questions</ref>\n\nThe [[Monsanto Citizenship Fund]] from [[Monsanto]] donated $1,500 on June 24, 2013 to Owens' 2014 campaign.<ref>http://query.nictusa.com/pdf/287/13941177287/13941177287.pdf</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*United States House of Representatives Committee on Appropriations'''\n**United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Defense\n**United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Homeland Security\n\nSource: [http://appropriations.house.gov/about/members/ House Appropriations Committee]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*[[Congressional Biomass Caucus]]\n*Congressional Center Aisle Caucus\n*Congressional Northern Border Caucus (Co-Chair)\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n*Sportsmen's Caucus\n\n==Personal life==\nOwens and his wife Jane have three children and four grandchildren. Jane was an [[early childhood education]] teacher and is currently the Director of Education and Outreach for [[Mountain Lake PBS]] in Plattsburgh.<ref name=\"jane\"/> He is a Roman Catholic.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"alice\">{{cite news|url=http://www.pressrepublican.com/archivesearch/local_story_153212416.html|title=Alice S. Owens|date=June 2, 2009|work=[[Press-Republican]]|accessdate=2009-11-05}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"appointed\">{{cite news|title=William Owens Appointed to College Council|date=October 22, 2004| url=http://www.plattsburgh.edu/news/index.php?wl_eid=299&wl_mode=more|publisher=[[State University of New York at Plattsburgh]]|accessdate=2009-11-05}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"changed race\">{{cite news|url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20091101/OPINION01/311019918/-1/OPINION|title= A changed race: Owens is best-equipped to represent NNY|date=November 1, 2009|work=Watertown Daily Times|accessdate=2009-11-03| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091104014210/http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20091101/OPINION01/311019918/-1/OPINION| archivedate= November 4, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"democrats nominate\">{{cite news| first=Mark|last=Weiner|title=Democrats nominate Bill Owens to run for Rep. John McHugh's seat in Congress|date=August 10, 2009| url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/democrats_nominate_bill_owens.html|work=[[The Post-Standard]]|accessdate=2009-11-05}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hat into ring\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressrepublican.com/homepage/local_story_204225439.html |title=Owens throws hat into ring \u00bb Local News |publisher=Press-Republican |date=July 23, 2009 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hr 1116\">{{cite web |url= http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h112-1116|title= HR 1116: Respect for Marriage Act|publisher= GovTrack.us |accessdate=July 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"jane\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mountainlake.org/our-community/station-information/about-us.html|title=Executive Staff|publisher=Mountain Lake PBS|accessdate=August 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"no on Stupak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20091107/BLOGS09/911079981/-1//BLOGS09 |title=Owens votes \"no\" on Stupak-Pitts amendment, \"yes\" on health care bill |publisher=Watertown Daily Times |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Observer\">{{cite news|url=http://www.observer.com/4850/meet-bill-owens-dccc-approved-non-democrat-house|title=Meet Bill Owens, a DCCC-Approved Non-Democrat for the House|last=Vielkind|first=Jimmy|date=August 11, 2009|work=[[The New York Observer]]|accessdate=2009-11-05| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091106034845/http://www.observer.com/4850/meet-bill-owens-dccc-approved-non-democrat-house| archivedate= November 6, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Observer10062009\">{{cite news|url=http://www.observer.com/5557/owens-financial-disclosure|title=Owens' Financial Disclosure|last=Vielkind|first=Jimmy|date=October 6, 2009|work=[[The New York Observer]]|accessdate=2009-11-05}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"open congress\">{{cite web|url=http://